    "# Design of Water Supply Systems\n",
    "\n",
    "Designing a **drinking water supply and treatment system** is one of the most complex and rewarding tasks in civil and environmental engineering. A successful design balances **technical performance**, **public health protection**, **cost**, and **sustainability**. Engineers must consider interacting factors such as demand estimation, water source protection, treatment processes, storage capacity, and distribution network configuration to ensure that a community’s water supply remains safe, reliable, and resilient over time.  \n",
    "\n",
    "The design process is guided by established manuals and standards, including the **American Water Works Association (AWWA)** *Manuals of Practice*, the **Ten States Standards**, and various state or municipal design guides. These resources provide consistent frameworks for planning, design, and construction — covering everything from pipe sizing and pump selection to treatment plant hydraulics and system redundancy.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Design as the Management of Constraints\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Design is the management of constraints** — balancing what must happen with what can happen.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Non-negotiable constraints** are dictated by physics, chemistry, and regulation.  \n",
    "  Water flows downhill unless energy is supplied to lift it; disinfectant residuals decay unless replenished; pressure cannot be maintained without sufficient head.  \n",
    "- **Negotiable constraints** are variables engineers can adjust — such as materials, layout, timing, budget, or aesthetics — to achieve performance within those physical limits.  \n",
    "\n",
    "In short, the designer’s role is to meet system needs by manipulating the negotiable variables to satisfy the non-negotiable requirements.  \n",
    "Analytical tools and computer models allow engineers to test designs virtually before construction begins — reducing uncertainty, avoiding costly field errors, and ensuring that the final design meets both technical and regulatory standards.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Hydraulic Principles in Design\n",
    "\n",
    "Hydraulics governs how water moves through pipes, pumps, tanks, and treatment processes. Sound hydraulic design ensures that adequate pressure and flow are maintained throughout the system — from the source, through the treatment plant, to the customer’s tap.  \n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Principles\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Flow and Pressure:** Equations such as *Bernoulli’s* and *Manning’s* help determine head loss, pipe sizes, pump capacities, and tank elevations. Typical pressures range from **40–80 psi**.  \n",
    "- **Energy and Grade Lines:** The *Hydraulic Grade Line (HGL)* helps visualize changes in energy along a system. Gravity flow, when possible, minimizes pumping and lowers operating costs.  \n",
    "- **System Optimization:** Modeling software such as **EPANET** or **WaterGEMS** allows simulation of network performance, including transient behavior and water age.\n",
    "\n",
    "In treatment plants, hydraulics ensures that each stage — sedimentation, filtration, or chemical dosing — operates effectively at design flow rates.  \n",
    "Designers also account for **transient effects** such as *water hammer* by using surge tanks, air-release valves, or slow-closing valves to protect system components.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Design Fundamentals for Water Systems\n",
    "\n",
    "All water system designs begin with four essential questions:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **How much water will be used?**  \n",
    "   Estimate current and future demands, including peak and fire-flow conditions.\n",
    "2. **Where are the supply sources located?**  \n",
    "   Identify groundwater wells, surface intakes, desalination plants, or rainwater systems — each has distinct implications.\n",
    "3. **Where are the consumption points?**  \n",
    "   Map demand centers to determine pressure zones, storage needs, and pump requirements.\n",
    "4. **How does demand vary with time?**  \n",
    "   Analyze diurnal and seasonal variations to size reservoirs and schedule pumping efficiently.\n",
    "\n",
    ":::{note}\n",
    "Building a modern database of local demand data would make an excellent *data-science project* (ENGR 1330).\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Transmission and Distribution Networks\n",
    "\n",
    "**Transmission mains** carry large volumes of water from sources or treatment plants to storage facilities.  \n",
    "**Distribution mains** deliver treated water to consumers through smaller interconnected pipes.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Common Layouts\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Tree (Branched) Systems:**  \n",
    "  Simple and economical; often used in rural areas but prone to stagnation and service disruption.\n",
    "- **Grid or Loop Systems:**  \n",
    "  Interconnected networks providing better pressure stability, redundancy, and water quality — preferred in most urban designs.\n",
    "- **Arterial Loop Systems:**  \n",
    "  Large backbone mains surrounding the service area, supplying smaller grids from multiple directions.\n",
    "\n",
    "> *Note:* Arterial loop and grid systems are functionally similar — terminology varies by locality.\n",
    "\n",
    "![](system-type.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "A well-designed system also includes **appurtenances** — valves, hydrants, blow-offs, and air-release devices — that aid operation and maintenance.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Design Guidance and Professional Standards\n",
    "\n",
    "Designers rely on three main categories of information:\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. Regulatory Documents\n",
    "Federal and state agencies, such as the **U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)** and state environmental departments, issue regulations governing system design, construction, and operation.  \n",
    "States may adopt more stringent rules than the federal minimums.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Design Manuals\n",
    "Local governments publish design manuals that define acceptable materials, construction practices, and testing procedures.  \n",
    "\n",
    "Representative examples:  \n",
    "- [Washington State Water System Design Manual (2018)](http://54.243.252.9/ce-3372-webroot/3-Readings/WashingtonWaterSystemDesignManual2018/WashingtonWaterSystemDesignManual2018.pdf)  \n",
    "- [City of Houston Design Manual](http://54.243.252.9/ce-3372-webroot/3-Readings/HoustonDesignManual/Houston.idm.pdf)  \n",
    "- [City of Lubbock Design Manual](http://54.243.252.9/ce-3372-webroot/3-Readings/LubbockTexasDesignManual/LubbockTexasDesignManual.pdf)  \n",
    "- [City of San Marcos Design Manual](http://54.243.252.9/ce-3372-webroot/3-Readings/SanMarcosTexasDesignManual/SanMarcosTexasDesignManual.pdf)\n",
    "\n",
    "> Always use the manual specific to your project’s jurisdiction — requirements and standards are updated frequently.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3. Professional and Manufacturer Literature\n",
    "For unusual or innovative projects, engineers may consult **manuals of practice**, **vendor specifications**, or **peer-reviewed research**.  \n",
    "Manuals and vendor data are generally preferred over research papers because they reflect proven, field-tested technologies and reduce design risk.\n",
    "\n"
