    "## Project Layout (Concept to Schematic)\n",
    "\n",
    "Most design manuals devote considerable space to **submittal and approval** requirements for drawings. Within the right-of-way, however, the **physical layout** is largely a hydraulic design choice.\n",
    "\n",
    "A typical early-stage workflow:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Prepare a **base map** and sketch a **grid** for the service area (scaled aerials help).  \n",
    "2. Place **nodes (junctions)** and assign **average demands**.  \n",
    "3. Apply **peak factors** and **fire-flow** requirements.  \n",
    "4. Add **future growth** allowances.  \n",
    "5. Test and iterate with a **hydraulic model**.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why nodes matter.** Models compute **pressure, demand, water quality, and velocity** at nodes against jurisdictional criteria (min/max values are in local guidance). Node spacing and exact placement are flexible on grids but matter more on **transmission mains** and in areas with steep grades.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Practice note:** You can design without software, but modern **free tools** (e.g., EPANET) are accurate and expected by many jurisdictions. **Commercial suites** often integrate better with drafting/asset tools and can repay their license in time savings.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Existing Data (What You Need to Lay Out a Network)\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Demand inputs:** Confirm with the owner; use land-use/zoning and local records for **current and projected** demands.  \n",
    "- **Map-based compilation:** Put demands on the base map; this drives **node placement** and **preliminary pipe diameters**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Pipe Diameter (Concept Rules)\n",
    "\n",
    "- Trench/installation is the major cost—**size for hydraulics**, not just material price.  \n",
    "- Meet **peak and fire-flow** while maintaining **adequate dynamic pressure**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Pressure Zones (When Terrain Drives Design)\n",
    "\n",
    "Large elevation differences require **zones** to avoid excessive low-area pressures and inadequate high-area pressures. As a rule of thumb, > ~**80 ft** elevation difference may trigger zoning.\n",
    "\n",
    "Hydraulic grade line checks:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\mathrm{HGL_{min}} = \\text{Highest Elev.} + 2.31 \\times \\text{Min. Pressure (psi)}\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\mathrm{HGL_{max}} = \\text{Lowest Elev.} + 2.31 \\times \\text{Max. Pressure (psi)}\n",
    "$"
